WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:15.000
I have some pretty stars in sight, and also I have the little white objects that seem to come from the capsule itself, and drift off.

00:16.000 --> 00:22.000
And if they are a yaw check, it's fantastic. I suspect that the star I see is...

00:22.000 --> 00:34.000
...Octurus would be very interesting. It is neither. It is one of the white objects.

00:37.000 --> 00:46.000
So I have two stars that are standing quite still. The white object actually looked like it came toward me, but it wasn't.

00:46.000 --> 00:58.000
You can actually see the particle there, going off. As John described, there's a lathe shaving. It's a very good description of it.

01:03.000 --> 01:08.000
My rates are now just about zero in all three axes.

01:16.000 --> 01:24.000
I still have light in the periscope, of course. I'm looking straight up.

01:25.000 --> 01:30.000
And yet, at this point, there's to be that my altitude is...

01:31.000 --> 01:39.000
I guess the couch here, I really can't pick it too well. Yeah, I'm just about inverted at this point.

01:39.000 --> 01:46.000
And that my nose is above the horizon.

01:51.000 --> 01:59.000
As a result, I notice that these particles keep tending aft on me, relative to me, at any time.

01:59.000 --> 02:15.000
The periscope is blocking out rather rapidly, at sunset.

02:20.000 --> 02:25.000
It's almost blocked out completely at this point, and it's really not usable.

02:25.000 --> 02:37.000
What's the pasti path?

02:37.000 --> 02:52.000
I'm not afraid of exactly with the camera, but I'll try to keep it backwards at that point.

02:52.000 --> 03:12.000
Getting a real burst of light in the window and I really don't know what it is.

03:12.000 --> 03:19.000
At this point I should be coming up on a sunset, 5 hours and 15 minutes.

03:19.000 --> 03:31.000
The telescope is dark. I must be just getting a last look at the horizon, yet I'm not down on it.

